AFFIDAVIT OF DISQUALIFICATION
Pursuant to MCR 2.003(C)(2)

STATE OF MICHIGAN )
                   ) ss.
COUNTY OF MUSKEGON )

ANDREW PIGORS, being first duly sworn, deposes and states as follows:

I. AFFIANT'S IDENTITY AND COMPETENCE

1. My name is Andrew Pigors. I am over 18 years of age, competent to testify, and make this Affidavit based on my personal knowledge of the facts stated herein.

2. I am the Plaintiff in the above-captioned matter and the biological father of Lincoln Pigors, born [DATE], who is the subject of custody and parenting time proceedings in this case.

3. I submit this Affidavit in support of my Motion for Disqualification of the Honorable Jenny L. McNeill pursuant to MCR 2.003(C)(2).

4. If called as a witness, I could and would testify competently to all matters stated in this Affidavit.

II. TIMELINESS OF MOTION

5. I first became aware of individual instances of ex parte orders and procedural irregularities as they occurred during 2025.

6. However, I did not discover the full pattern and scope of the systematic bias and ex parte conduct until I conducted a comprehensive review of the court file and all orders entered in this case on or about [DATE].

7. Upon discovering that twenty-four (24) of fifty-five (55) orders (44%) were entered ex parte without notice to me, I immediately consulted with legal resources and determined that grounds for disqualification existed.

8. This Motion is filed within fourteen (14) days of discovering the factual basis for the pattern of bias and appearance of impropriety requiring disqualification.

III. PATTERN OF EX PARTE ORDERS WITHOUT NOTICE

9. Since the inception of this case in January 2025, Judge McNeill has entered twenty-four (24) separate orders that materially affected my parental rights without providing me notice or an opportunity to be heard.

10. These ex parte orders were entered on the following dates (with number of orders):
    • February 12, 2025: 2 orders
    • February 28, 2025: 1 order
    • March 15, 2025: 3 orders
    • April 3, 2025: 2 orders
    • April 22, 2025: 1 order
    • May 7, 2025: 2 orders
    • May 29, 2025: 1 order
    • June 10, 2025: 2 orders
    • June 24, 2025: 1 order
    • July 8, 2025: 3 orders
    • July 22, 2025: 1 order
    • August 8, 2025: 5 orders (same day)

11. Out of approximately fifty-five (55) total orders entered by Judge McNeill in this case, twenty-four (24) were entered ex parte, representing 43.6% of all orders.

12. This pattern demonstrates systematic disregard for my due process rights and Michigan Court Rules requiring notice.

A. August 8, 2025 - Five Ex Parte Orders Same Day

13. On August 8, 2025, Judge McNeill entered five (5) separate orders affecting my custody and parenting time rights, all on the same day, without any notice to me:

    Order 1: Temporary Suspension of Parenting Time
    • Suspended my parenting time "effective immediately"
    • Based solely on Defendant's unverified motion
    • No hearing scheduled or conducted
    • I received no notice until order was entered and parenting time already denied
    
    Order 2: Modification of Custody Evaluation Requirements
    • Changed terms of custody evaluation over my objection
    • I had filed response opposing this change
    • Judge did not review my response before entering order
    
    Order 3: Personal Protection Order Extension
    • Extended PPO without hearing
    • I had requested hearing to contest extension
    • No opportunity to present evidence or cross-examine Defendant
    
    Order 4: Friend of Court Investigation
    • Ordered FOC investigation based on Defendant's allegations
    • No notice that motion would be heard
    • Investigation commenced before I was aware order existed
    
    Order 5: Denial of My Motion for Makeup Parenting Time
    • Denied my pending motion without hearing
    • No explanation provided
    • Defendant's identical motion granted two weeks earlier

14. I did not receive notice of any of these orders until August 12, 2025, four days after they were entered and implemented.

15. By the time I received notice, I had already been denied parenting time on August 9 and August 10, 2025, pursuant to Order 1.

16. The cumulative effect of five ex parte orders entered on the same day, without notice or opportunity to respond, demonstrates a pattern of systematic bias against me.

B. March 15, 2025 - Ex Parte Modification of Custody

17. On March 15, 2025, Judge McNeill entered an order modifying the temporary custody arrangement, granting Defendant primary physical custody.

18. This order was entered without notice to me and without a hearing.

19. The order was based on Defendant's ex parte motion filed March 14, 2025, which I did not receive until March 18, 2025.

20. Judge McNeill entered the order within 24 hours of Defendant's filing, making it impossible for me to respond even if I had received notice.

21. This order fundamentally altered my parental rights and access to my child without affording me due process.

22. When I filed a motion for reconsideration on March 25, 2025, it was denied on April 8, 2025, without a hearing and without substantive analysis of the due process violation.

C. May 7, 2025 - Ex Parte Parenting Time Suspension

23. On May 7, 2025, Judge McNeill entered two orders: (1) suspending my parenting time for two weeks, and (2) ordering me to undergo a psychological evaluation.

24. I received no notice that these motions would be heard or decided on May 7, 2025.

25. The suspension order stated it was "effective immediately" and applied to parenting time scheduled for May 10-11, 2025.

26. I did not learn of the suspension until I arrived for my scheduled parenting time on May 10, 2025, and Defendant informed me that Judge McNeill had suspended my time.

27. I had made plans for that parenting time, including purchasing tickets to a minor league baseball game that Lincoln and I had been planning to attend together.

28. The psychological evaluation order required me to pay $2,500 for an evaluation, without any hearing to determine whether such evaluation was necessary or appropriate.

29. I was not given an opportunity to present evidence that I had already completed a psychological evaluation in 2024, which found no concerns.

IV. SYSTEMATIC BIAS AGAINST PLAINTIFF

A. Disparate Treatment: Motions Granted vs. Denied

30. Judge McNeill has demonstrated a clear pattern of granting Defendant's motions while denying my substantially identical motions.

31. During the period from January 2025 to December 2025:
    • Defendant filed 18 motions; Judge McNeill granted 15 (83%)
    • I filed 22 motions; Judge McNeill granted 4 (18%)

32. Examples of disparate treatment:

    Motion for Makeup Parenting Time:
    • Defendant filed May 15, 2025 → Granted May 22, 2025 (7 days)
    • I filed July 20, 2025 → Denied August 8, 2025 (19 days), no hearing
    
    Motion for Reconsideration:
    • Defendant filed June 3, 2025 → Granted June 15, 2025, with hearing
    • I filed June 10, 2025 → Denied June 25, 2025, no hearing, no explanation
    
    Motion to Modify Parenting Time:
    • Defendant filed April 1, 2025 → Granted April 10, 2025, ex parte
    • I filed April 25, 2025 → Denied May 30, 2025, after two hearings and extensive briefing

B. Disparate Treatment: Response Times

33. Judge McNeill responds to Defendant's motions significantly faster than to my motions:
    • Average time to rule on Defendant's motions: 8.3 days
    • Average time to rule on my motions: 47.6 days
    • Median time for Defendant: 7 days
    • Median time for me: 32 days

34. On six occasions, Judge McNeill ruled on Defendant's motions the same day they were filed.

35. Judge McNeill has never ruled on any of my motions on the same day filed.

36. The longest delay for Defendant's motion: 21 days.

37. The longest delay for my motion: 94 days (motion filed September 3, 2025; ruled on December 6, 2025).

C. Credibility Determinations Without Evidentiary Hearings

38. Judge McNeill has made adverse credibility findings against me without conducting evidentiary hearings where I could testify or present evidence.

39. On April 22, 2025, Judge McNeill's order stated: "The Court finds Plaintiff's explanations not credible and his conduct concerning."

40. This finding was made based solely on written pleadings, without any hearing where I testified or was subject to cross-examination.

41. I requested an evidentiary hearing to present my evidence. My request was denied.

42. In contrast, Judge McNeill has accepted Defendant's allegations as true without requiring corroborating evidence or testimony.

43. On July 8, 2025, Judge McNeill's order stated: "The Court credits Defendant's testimony regarding Plaintiff's behavior."

44. However, no testimony was taken on July 8, 2025. The order was entered based on Defendant's motion and affidavit, without a hearing.

D. Prejudicial Statements at October 15, 2025 Hearing

45. At the hearing on October 15, 2025, Judge McNeill made statements that revealed prejudgment and bias against me.

46. Before any testimony was taken, Judge McNeill stated: "I've reviewed the file, Mr. Pigors, and I have concerns about your conduct throughout these proceedings."

47. When I attempted to explain my position, Judge McNeill interrupted and stated: "I don't need to hear excuses. The pattern here is clear."

48. Judge McNeill referenced allegations that had never been proven or admitted into evidence, treating them as established facts.

49. When my witness attempted to testify about Defendant's violations of court orders, Judge McNeill stated: "That's not relevant to what we're here for today."

50. Yet when Defendant's witness testified about alleged conduct by me that was not noticed in the motion, Judge McNeill allowed the testimony and considered it in her ruling.

51. The transcript of the October 15, 2025 hearing demonstrates Judge McNeill's bias and predetermination of issues before hearing evidence.

V. VIOLATIONS OF CANONS OF JUDICIAL CONDUCT

A. Canon 2: Impropriety and Appearance of Impropriety

52. Canon 2 requires judges to avoid impropriety and the appearance of impropriety in all activities.

53. Judge McNeill's pattern of conduct creates a clear appearance of impropriety:
    • 44% of orders entered ex parte suggests favoritism toward one party
    • Granting 83% of one party's motions while granting only 18% of other party's motions
    • Making factual findings without evidentiary hearings
    • Accepting one party's allegations as true while rejecting other party's evidence

54. Any reasonable person reviewing this record would question whether I am receiving fair and impartial treatment.

B. Canon 3(B)(7): Ex Parte Communications

55. Canon 3(B)(7) prohibits judges from initiating, permitting, or considering ex parte communications concerning a pending matter.

56. Judge McNeill has systematically violated this Canon by:
    • Entertaining ex parte motions from Defendant without notice to me
    • Entering orders based on ex parte submissions
    • Making substantive rulings without affording me opportunity to respond
    • Conducting the equivalent of one-sided hearings by ruling immediately upon Defendant's filings

57. The pattern of ex parte conduct is not isolated incidents but a systematic practice affecting nearly half of all orders entered.

C. Canon 3(B)(8): Prompt Disposition

58. Canon 3(B)(8) requires judges to dispose of matters promptly, efficiently, and fairly.

59. While Judge McNeill has been prompt in ruling on Defendant's motions (average 8.3 days), she has been substantially delayed in ruling on my motions (average 47.6 days).

60. This disparity in processing times denies me equal treatment and creates appearance that my motions receive less consideration.

61. The requirement of "fairness" in Canon 3(B)(8) requires equal treatment of parties, which has been systematically denied.

VI. SPECIFIC INSTANCES OF DEMONSTRATED BIAS

A. Denial of Motions for Reconsideration

62. I have filed eight (8) motions for reconsideration during these proceedings, citing palpable errors of fact and law.

63. Judge McNeill has denied all eight motions without conducting hearings and without substantive analysis of the alleged errors.

64. MCR 2.119(F) requires courts to grant reconsideration when there is a palpable error by which the court and parties have been misled, or when reconsideration is necessary to prevent manifest injustice.

65. My motions documented clear factual errors in Judge McNeill's orders, including:
    • Finding that I failed to appear at a hearing when court records showed I appeared and testified
    • Stating that I did not respond to a motion when my response was filed timely and appears in the court file
    • Crediting allegations that were factually disproven by documentary evidence I submitted

66. Despite documenting these palpable errors, Judge McNeill denied reconsideration without explanation.

67. In contrast, Defendant has filed three (3) motions for reconsideration, all of which were granted, with hearings held on each.

B. Personal Protection Order Proceedings

68. This case involves multiple Personal Protection Orders filed by Defendant against me.

69. Judge McNeill has treated these PPO proceedings in a manner that systematically disadvantages me:
    • Granting ex parte PPOs based solely on Defendant's allegations
    • Extending PPOs without hearings
    • Refusing to consider my evidence of false allegations
    • Using PPO allegations as basis for custody decisions without requiring proof

70. On June 24, 2025, Judge McNeill extended a PPO for an additional year without conducting a hearing, despite my request for a hearing and my submission of evidence that the original allegations were false.

71. On July 8, 2025, Judge McNeill issued an opinion stating that the existence of the PPO created a presumption against me in custody proceedings.

72. However, Michigan law does not create such a presumption. MCL 722.27 requires proof of domestic violence, not merely the existence of a PPO.

73. By treating the mere existence of a PPO (which was granted ex parte without a hearing) as establishing domestic violence, Judge McNeill effectively eliminated my due process rights to contest the allegations.

C. Best Interests Determinations

74. Michigan's Child Custody Act requires courts to make custody determinations based on the best interests factors in MCL 722.23.

75. Judge McNeill's custody orders do not include analysis of the best interests factors.

76. On March 15, 2025, Judge McNeill modified custody to give Defendant primary physical custody. The order stated this was in Lincoln's "best interests" but did not analyze any of the statutory factors.

77. I had submitted extensive evidence on each best interests factor, including:
    • Evidence of my strong bond with Lincoln
    • Evidence of my capacity and disposition to provide Lincoln with food, clothing, medical care, and other material needs
    • Evidence of Lincoln's adjustment to home, school, and community
    • Evidence of my moral fitness
    • Evidence of my mental and physical health

78. Judge McNeill's order did not address this evidence or explain how the best interests factors supported the custody modification.

79. When I filed a motion requesting findings on the best interests factors, Judge McNeill denied the motion without explanation.

VII. DUE PROCESS VIOLATIONS

80. The Fourteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution guarantees due process of law before deprivation of life, liberty, or property.

81. The United States Supreme Court has held that parents have a fundamental liberty interest in the care, custody, and control of their children. Troxel v. Granville, 530 US 57 (2000).

82. Before a court may deprive a parent of custody or parenting time, due process requires:
    • Notice of the proceedings
    • Opportunity to be heard
    • Opportunity to present evidence
    • Opportunity to cross-examine adverse witnesses
    • Decision by a neutral and impartial tribunal

83. Judge McNeill's pattern of ex parte orders has systematically denied me these due process protections.

84. Specific due process violations include:

    a) Orders entered without notice (24 instances documented above);
    
    b) Orders based on allegations I had no opportunity to rebut;
    
    c) Credibility determinations made without hearing my testimony;
    
    d) Denial of requests for evidentiary hearings;
    
    e) Factual findings made without evidentiary basis;
    
    f) Suspension of parenting time without showing of immediate harm to child.

VIII. HARM TO PLAINTIFF AND CHILD

85. Judge McNeill's conduct has caused me substantial and irreparable harm:

    a) I have been denied meaningful parenting time with Lincoln for extended periods based on ex parte orders;
    
    b) My fundamental constitutional right to parent my child has been violated;
    
    c) I have incurred substantial legal expenses attempting to vindicate my rights;
    
    d) My reputation has been damaged by orders based on unproven allegations;
    
    e) My relationship with Lincoln has been severely damaged by prolonged separations.

86. Lincoln has suffered harm from being separated from his father:

    a) Lincoln has expressed to third parties that he misses me and wants to spend time with me;
    
    b) Lincoln's therapist has reported that Lincoln is experiencing anxiety and emotional distress related to the custody situation;
    
    c) Lincoln has been deprived of the benefit of a relationship with a loving, fit parent.

87. The harm to both Lincoln and me continues as long as Judge McNeill presides over this case, because I cannot have confidence that I will receive fair and impartial treatment.

IX. OBJECTIVE STANDARD FOR DISQUALIFICATION

88. Under MCR 2.003(C)(1)(b), the question is whether "a person of ordinary prudence in the judge's position, knowing all of the facts known to the judge, would have reasonable basis to question the judge's impartiality."

89. A person of ordinary prudence, knowing the following facts, would have reasonable basis to question Judge McNeill's impartiality:

    a) 44% of all orders entered ex parte without notice to one party;
    
    b) 83% of one party's motions granted vs. 18% of other party's motions granted;
    
    c) Average 8.3 days to rule on one party's motions vs. 47.6 days for other party;
    
    d) Credibility determinations made against one party without evidentiary hearing;
    
    e) All motions for reconsideration by one party denied; all by other party granted;
    
    f) Prejudicial statements made at hearings before evidence presented;
    
    g) Pattern of accepting one party's allegations as true while disregarding other party's evidence.

90. These facts, viewed objectively, create more than reasonable basis to question impartiality—they demonstrate clear appearance of bias.

X. GOOD FAITH BASIS FOR MOTION

91. I submit this Motion in good faith based on substantial grounds for disqualification.

92. I do not seek to delay proceedings; I seek a fair and impartial tribunal.

93. The facts stated in this Affidavit are true and can be verified from the court file and transcripts.

94. I respectfully request that the Chief Judge review the court file, including:
    • All orders entered by Judge McNeill with dates of filing and entry
    • All motions filed by both parties with dates of filing and ruling
    • Transcripts of hearings, particularly October 15, 2025
    • Evidence of notice (or lack thereof) for ex parte orders

95. Such review will confirm the pattern of conduct alleged in this Affidavit.

XI. CONCLUSION

96. The facts stated in this Affidavit establish both actual bias and appearance of impropriety requiring disqualification under MCR 2.003(C)(1).

97. Judge McNeill has demonstrated personal bias against me through systematic disparate treatment, prejudicial statements, and credibility determinations made without hearing my testimony.

98. A person of ordinary prudence would have reasonable basis to question Judge McNeill's impartiality based on the objective facts documented above.

99. I cannot receive a fair and impartial hearing before Judge McNeill, and justice requires reassignment of this case to another judge.

I declare under penalty of perjury that the foregoing is true and correct.

